title: Fix onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB for protobuf by not forcing legacy protobuf

The option `protobuf_MODULE_COMPATIBLE` is for legacy protobuf. Since onnx and onnxruntime have both moved to protobuf 3.12+, this is no longer legacy and we don't need to require legacy mode.

- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): macOS 11.6 (Big Sur)

build.sh --config MinSizeRel \
                   --parallel \
                   --minimal_build \
                   --disable_exceptions \
                   --disable_ml_ops \
                   --skip_tests \
                   --skip_submodule_sync

The final build (link log is as follows);

```
Undefined symbols for architecture x86_64:
  "_NSLog", referenced from:
      onnxruntime::logging::AppleLogSink::SendImpl(std::__1::chrono::time_point<std::__1::chrono::system_clock, std::__1::chrono::duration<long long, std::__1::ratio<1l, 1000000l> > > const&, std::__1::basic_string<char, std::__1::char_traits<char>, std::__1::allocator<char> > const&, onnxruntime::logging::Capture const&) in libonnxruntime_common.a(apple_log_sink.mm.o)

  "_cpuinfo_initialize", referenced from:
      onnxruntime::CPUIDInfo::CPUIDInfo() in libonnxruntime_common.a(cpuid_info.cc.o)
ld: symbol(s) not found for architecture x86_64
clang: error: linker command failed with exit code 1 (use -v to see invocation)
```

**Expected behavior**
build (link) complete successfully

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Additional context**
As investigating the issue, I found `cmake/onnxruntime_common.cmake` is as follows;
```
...
if(WIN32)
    list(APPEND onnxruntime_common_src_patterns
         "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/windows/*.h"
         "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/windows/*.cc"
         "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/windows/logging/*.h"
         "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/windows/logging/*.cc"
    )
    # Windows platform adapter code uses advapi32, which isn't linked in by default in desktop ARM
    if (NOT WINDOWS_STORE)
        list(APPEND onnxruntime_EXTERNAL_LIBRARIES advapi32)
    endif()
else()
    list(APPEND onnxruntime_common_src_patterns
         "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/posix/*.h"
         "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/posix/*.cc"
    )

    if (onnxruntime_USE_SYSLOG)
        list(APPEND onnxruntime_common_src_patterns
            "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/posix/logging/*.h"
            "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/posix/logging/*.cc"
        )
    endif()

    if (CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME STREQUAL "Android")
        list(APPEND onnxruntime_common_src_patterns
            "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/android/logging/*.h"
            "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/android/logging/*.cc"
        )
    endif()

    if (APPLE)
        list(APPEND onnxruntime_common_src_patterns
            "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/apple/logging/*.h"
            "${ONNXRUNTIME_ROOT}/core/platform/apple/logging/*.mm"
            )
    endif()
endif()
```

When building on macOS, the flag `APPLE` is on, and it is trying to use `core/platform/apple/logging/*.mm`, which is root cause of the error. (I found previous versions are using just `core/platform/posix/logging/*.cc`)

And another error is from `cpuinfo_initialize` from `core/common/cpuid_info.cc`, there is no `cpuinfo_initialize` function defined in system libraries on macOS. 

How can I fix or bypass those above errors?

title: Expose option to strictly enforce shape and type correctness
body:
#2199 made it so that shape and type errors (e.g. mismatches between the shape of an output as stated in in the ONNX graph and what is inferred) are not fatal UNLESS the model is using the latest opset version. This allowed a bug in the PyTorch-ONNX exporter to go unnoticed for several months (see https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/67121/commits/79e8bf58bb0e0ca690880fbd40a80ebd69040e2b).

Thus I'm requesting an API to explicitly request strict enforcement of correctness, regardless of opset version.

CC @BowenBao @skottmckay @gramalingam

**Description**: Switch TensorShape from being a std::vector to having a small buffer optimization so that the common cases do not allocate heap memory. Larger shapes will still allocate memory as before

print(f"sklearn: {sklearn.__version__}")

NUMS = [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14]
CHARS = string.ascii_letters + string.digits

model = Pipeline(
    [
        (
            "features",
            ColumnTransformer(
                [
                    (
                        "char_freq",
                        TfidfVectorizer(
                            norm="l1",
                            analyzer="char",
                            use_idf=False,
                            lowercase=True,

                            analyzer="word",
                            use_idf=False,
                            lowercase=True,

                        ),
                        "doc",
                    ),

            ),
        ),
        (
            "model",
            LogisticRegression(random_state=42),
        ),
    ]
)


def get_sample(w: np.ndarray) -> str:
    n = random.choice(NUMS)
    return "".join(random.choices(CHARS, weights=w, k=n))


def make_data() -> pd.DataFrame:

    df["doc"] = df.apply(lambda x: get_sample(w1) if x["label"] == 1 else get_sample(w0), axis=1)
    return df


df = make_data()
model.fit(df[["doc"]], df["label"])

title: Improve transfered time from ort to torch
body:
**Description**:

backward method creates many gradients stored in one OrtValueVector. The ownership of the data is then transfered to pytorch. This process needs the creation of a torch tensor for every OrtValue. One transfer costs:

* an allocation to a DLPack structure in ort
* the creation of a capsule to hold it
* the creation of a tensor in pytorch
* the allocation of another structure in pytorch
* the copy of a DLPack structure

The changes proposes to remove the first two steps. The DLPack structure is allocated on the stack and reused for every element of OrtValueVector, the capsule is also reused to save the creation of one python object. The cost of the transfer back to pytorch is approximatively reduced by 30%-50%.

All conversions from OrtValueVector to tuple of torch.tensor should go through function `_utils._ortvalues_to_torch_tensor`. If there is no boolean OrtValue, the function is 30% faster than the previous implementation.

**Motivation and Context**
- Performance: method forward and backward needs to take ownership of tensors from pytorch and give owernship of output or gradient. When there are many tensors to process (> 100 hundred), this can take a few milliseconds. This process cannot be efficiently parallelized. It creates many python object in a short time and goes through the GIL many time. Parallelization is inefficient in that case.

The conversion of 10 OrtValueVector of 100 OrtValue currently takes 0.003257s and 0.000871s with these changes. Measures obtained with the following script.

```
import time
import numpy 
from onnxruntime.capi._pybind_state import (
    OrtValue as C_OrtValue,
    OrtDevice as C_OrtDevice,
    OrtMemType, OrtValueVector)
from onnxruntime.capi import _pybind_state as C
import torch


def create_ortvalues(device=None):
    if device is None:
        device = C_OrtDevice(C_OrtDevice.cpu(), OrtMemType.DEFAULT, 0)
    memo = []
    ovect = OrtValueVector()
    for i in range(0, 100):
        vect = numpy.random.randn(2, 10).astype(numpy.float32)
        memo.append(vect)
        ort_value = C_OrtValue.ortvalue_from_numpy(vect, device)
        ovect.push_back(ort_value)
    return ovect, memo

def to_tensor_loop1(ovs):
    return tuple(torch.from_dlpack(ov.to_dlpack()) for ov in ovs)


def to_tensor_loop2(ovs):
    return tuple(torch._C._from_dlpack(ov.to_dlpack()) for ov in ovs)

def to_tensor_vector(ovs):
    return tuple(ovs.to_dlpacks(torch._C._from_dlpack))



fcts = [(to_tensor_loop1, None),
        (to_tensor_loop2, None),
        (to_tensor_vector, None)]


if False: # ort device
    # How to create a OrtValue with device == 'ort'?
    device_ort = C_OrtDevice(0, OrtMemType.DEFAULT, 0)
    print(device_ort.device_type())

    def ov2torch_eager(ovs):
        return tuple(C.to_aten_ort_device_tensor(ov) for ov in ovs)

    fcts.append((ov2torch_eager, device_ort))

for fct, dev in fcts:
    # check
    res = []
    for i in range(0, 10):
        ovs, memo = create_ortvalues(dev)
        begin = time.perf_counter()
        fct(ovs)
        end = time.perf_counter()
        delay = end - begin
        res.append(delay)

    print("%s: size=%d %f" % (fct.__name__, len(memo), sum(res)))
    print(res)
```

title: QDQ tool modification
body:
**Description**: 
This PR makes two changes:

1. Add op_types_to_exclude_output_quantization for users to specify nodes to exclude output quantization.
For example, user can specify op_types_to_exclude_output_quantization = ["MatMul", "Add"]
The reason to do so is that in some cases, for example QDQ BERT model for TensorRT, adding QDQ for node's output may end up with worse accuracy. So, we don't recommend to add QDQ to node's output under such condition.

2. Add option to force QDQ appear as a pair when adding QDQ to weighted inputs. 
User can specify {'AddQDQPairToWeight': True} or {'AddQDQPairToWeight': False}.
In some cases, for example QDQ BERT model for TensorRT, QDQ should always appear as a pair.
For our quantization tool, we do quantization on Dequantizelinear's input to remove Quantizelinear as optimization for weights. Therefore, we need to disable this optimization.
